{"id":"astro-ph/0412364","submitter":"Axel Brandenburg","authors":"A. Brandenburg (Nordita), N. E. L. Haugen (Trondheim), P. J.\n  K\\\"apyl\\\"a (Oulu and KIS), C. Sandin (Stockholm)","title":"The problem of small and large scale fields in the solar dynamo","comments":"to appear in Astron. Nachr., in honour of the retirement of Michael\n  Stix","journal-ref":"Astron.Nachr. 326 (2005) 174-185","doi":"10.1002/asna.200410373","report-no":"NORDITA-2004-103","categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Three closely related stumbling blocks of solar mean field dynamo theory are\ndiscussed: how dominant are the small scale fields, how is the alpha effect\nquenched, and whether magnetic and current helicity fluxes alleviate the\nquenching? It is shown that even at the largest currently available resolution\nthere is no clear evidence of power law scaling of the magnetic and kinetic\nenergy spectra in turbulence. However, using subgrid scale modeling, some\nindications of asymptotic equipartition can be found. The frequently used first\norder smoothing approach to calculate the alpha effect and other transport\ncoefficients is contrasted with the superior minimal tau approximation. The\npossibility of catastrophic alpha quenching is discussed as a result of\nmagnetic helicity conservation. Magnetic and current helicity fluxes are shown\nto alleviate catastrophic quenching in the presence of shear. Evidence for\nstrong large scale dynamo action, even in the absence of helicity in the\nforcing, is presented.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 15 Dec 2004 17:19:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
